She hoped the law’s $350 billion for small-business loans would help them avoid laying off any of their five employees, whom she said are like family.
A set of new regulations for implementing the law, issued by the Small Business Administration, prohibits small-business owners with criminal records from accessing the desperately needed loans.
The Small Business Administration has yet to respond to questions from The Marshall Project about its new loan guidelines.
In the past, negotiations between the Small Business Administration and banks about steps required to make sure this doesn’t happen have often been extensive.
The second loan program is also bewildering many applicants with criminal records.